# Caching — why & strategies

DB query: **~1 ms** (hundreds under load). Cache lookup: **microseconds** — 3–4 orders faster. A cache in front of the DB = the **highest-leverage** perf change.

**Shape:** check cache → **hit** returns · **miss** → DB, write to cache, return. Next reads within **TTL** get the fast path.

**Services:** **ElastiCache** (Redis/Valkey/Memcached, general) · **DAX** (write-through, **DynamoDB-only**).

## The patterns

- **Lazy loading (cache-aside)** — read cache; miss → DB → write back. Only caches what's read; outage just slows. But **first read misses** + can go **stale**.
- **Write-through** — write to **both**; reads never miss written data. Cost: double-write, may cache unused data.
- **TTL** — per-entry expiry; the staleness bound.

**Default:** lazy loading + TTL; add write-through where read-after-write matters.
